The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

Change-Id: I13e1daf113c490d48bef11d981bd02fd8eb50d02","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/e9e46e402517fdc2a80c9857dc5278493b6250c0"},{"sha":"44b9b8339c5065c2970b828f8a00692ef58e200f","author":{"name":"Mehdi Amini","email":"808100943be7b7010123d78912f654820a5ee1c1@google.com"},"message":"Add support to MLIR TensorFlow dialect for "placeholder attributes"

The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

Change-Id: Ic33a51ed804804d33624026eb674a94e4b9e5b36","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/44b9b8339c5065c2970b828f8a00692ef58e200f"},{"sha":"5d9a0c58f00b6c9b498f65b8d851568d594b3a34","author":{"name":"Yuanzhong Xu","email":"4a8be3b63a1468bbe5756287a5d3023353bf211f@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Custom partitioning of rotate pattern (concat(slice, slice))

Moved the custom call handler to a separate file. Now recognize patterns of concat(slice,slice) and turn eligible ones into custom rotate ops. Then use collective permute to partition the rotate ops.

Bug fix: SpmdBuilder didn't override base Builder; when no instructions were created, logger could crash.

Change-Id: I13e1daf113c490d48bef11d981bd02fd8eb50d02","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/e9e46e402517fdc2a80c9857dc5278493b6250c0"},{"sha":"44b9b8339c5065c2970b828f8a00692ef58e200f","author":{"name":"Mehdi Amini","email":"808100943be7b7010123d78912f654820a5ee1c1@google.com"},"message":"Add support to MLIR TensorFlow dialect for "placeholder attributes"

The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"

* Add feature flag: enableStrongMemoryCleanup

Add a feature flag that will test doing a recursive clean of an unmount
node. This will disconnect the fiber graph making leaks less severe.

* Detach sibling pointers in old child list

When a fiber is deleted, it's still part of the previous (alternate)
parent fiber's list of children. Because children are a linked list, an
earlier sibling that's still alive will be connected to the deleted
fiber via its alternate:


  live fiber
  --alternate--> previous live fiber
  --sibling--> deleted fiber

We can't disconnect `alternate` on nodes that haven't been deleted
yet, but we can disconnect the `sibling` and `child` pointers.

Will use this feature flag to test the memory impact.

* Combine into single enum flag

I combined `enableStrongMemoryCleanup` and `enableDetachOldChildList`
into a single enum flag. The flag has three possible values. Each level
is a superset of the previous one and performs more aggressive clean up.

We will use this to compare the memory impact of each level.

* Add Flow type to new host config method

* Re-use existing recursive clean up path

We already have a recursive loop that visits every deleted fiber. We
can re-use that one for clean up instead of adding another one.

Co-authored-by: Andrew Clark <git@andrewclark.io>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lalalazero/react/commits/25bfa287f6c49950d8ea16f542716835683442d6"}]

* Add samples to a fold with least num samples

* Better variable naming

* Add section to documentation

* Add changelist and reference to original kernel

* Better naming for least populated class check

* Add changelog entry

* Better variable names

* Extracted best_fold search into a separate method

* Switch name from label_idx to class_idx

* Fix image numbers to match updated example

* Add author

* Add SGKF visualization to docs

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

[{"sha":"4472d7512de4477c635d1d7dbcd2c5683a45bfb3","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Passive effect updates are never sync (#21215)

I screwed this up in #21082. Got confused by the < versus > thing again.

The helper functions are annoying, too, because I always forget the
intended order of the arguments. But they're still helpful because when
we refactor the type we only have the change the logic in one place.

Added a regression test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/4472d7512de4477c635d1d7dbcd2c5683a45bfb3"},{"sha":"23142b0deceba43e278bd6748235c2babdd6ef2e","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Don't rely on `finishedLanes` for passive effects (#21233)

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/23142b0deceba43e278bd6748235c2babdd6ef2e"}]

[{"sha":"dd8552ae0d82afed66fec649ee5c044c69c65e92","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"yarn test: Default to bleeding edge configuration (#21238)

My personal workflow is to develop against the www-modern release
channel, with the variant flags enabled, because it encompasses the
largest set of features. Then I rely on CI to run the tests against
all the other configurations.

So in practice, I almost always run

```
yarn test -r=www-modern --variant TEST_FILE
```

instead of

```
yarn test TEST_FILE
```

So, I've updated the `yarn test` command to use those options

This commit tries to gracefully handle the case where the foreman user
is not of pulp group and removes that requirement.
Ti achieve this it  does the following:
1) Ignores checking the 'pulp' permissions in the import path. This job
   is best left to pulp (https://pulp.plan.io/issues/7549)
2) Makes sure that the toc name is gotten from the exporter task output
   rather than scanning the directory. This removes the requirement of
   foreman/vagrant user having to check a pulp directory.
3) Removes the import 'skip' strategy on failed import. Instead it
   pauses on error and requires the user to skip and delete the content
   view version.

channel, with the variant flags enabled, because it encompasses the
largest set of features. Then I rely on CI to run the tests against
all the other configurations.

```
yarn test -r=www-modern --variant TEST_FILE
```

instead of

```
yarn test TEST_FILE
```

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

[{"sha":"dd8552ae0d82afed66fec649ee5c044c69c65e92","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"yarn test: Default to bleeding edge configuration (#21238)

My personal workflow is to develop against the www-modern release
channel, with the variant flags enabled, because it encompasses the
largest set of features. Then I rely on CI to run the tests against
all the other configurations.

So in practice, I almost always run

```
yarn test -r=www-modern --variant TEST_FILE
```

instead of

```
yarn test TEST_FILE
```

So, I've updated the `yarn test` command to use those options
by default.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Muhammadariesta/react/commits/dd8552ae0d82afed66fec649ee5c044c69c65e92"},{"sha":"686b635b7141511a7bbe751430f6680fc5cca2e2","author":{"name":"Joshua Gross","email":"d29bc49d09431027501fa5b225ec1424670862ff@gmail.com"},"message":"Prevent reading canonical property of null (#21242)

[{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

Signed-off-by: Cam <gh@sparr.email>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sparrc/moby/commits/8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1"}]

* Bump version number

* Remove Scheduler indirection

I originally kept the React PriorityLevel and Scheduler PriorityLevel
types separate in case there was a versioning mismatch between the two
modules. However, it looks like we're going to keep the Scheduler module
private in the short to medium term, and longer term the public
interface will match postTask. So, I've removed the extra indirection
(the switch statements that convert between the two types).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/72acc09e73c8c2fff92353a7f3a98836812c038b"},{"sha":"9c87915fb5cd76cc59b9f6e20af01effaba01bd4","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Move sync task queue to its own module (#21109)

The sync task queue is React-specific and doesn't really have anything
to do with Scheduler. We'd keep using it even once `postTask` exists.

By separating that part out, `SchedulerWithReactIntegration` is now
just a module that re-exports the Scheduler API. So I unforked it.
When we switch to ES Modules, we can remove this re-exporting module.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/9c87915fb5cd76cc59b9f6e20af01effaba01bd4"},{"sha":"b48bbaa21c14b8e2688091521f6496a5c401fc5d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: flushSync changes priority inside effect (#21122)

When called from inside an effect, flushSync cannot synchronously flush
its updates because React is already working. So we fire a warning.

However, we should still change the priority of the updates to sync so
that they flush at the end of the current task.

This only affects useEffect because updates inside useLayoutEffect (and

synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368186304
Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368225681
Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

[{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/cb1a834324c7e1169b0c8d06137f5b4e092c187f"},{"sha":"60f378f918194101bcb82faedc07115d483e5b32","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Entangled expired lanes with SyncLane (#21083)

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

Removed `import io` as it's not used","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/8399d79b33615dd9fa3e0edc668b62dcd88835d6"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

[{"sha":"7b14fd5391e6b1d3b3eba46ff99dc7b7dbdc1013","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

[{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

I recently started using `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` to check if there were any pending
passive effects (530027a). `pendingPassiveEffectsLanes` is the value of
`root.finishedLanes` at the beginning of the commit phase. When there
are pending passive effects, it should always be a non-zero value,
because it represents the lanes used to render the effects.

But it turns out that `root.finishedLanes` isn't always correct.
Sometimes it's `NoLanes` even when there's a new commit.

I found this while investigating an internal bug report. The only repro
I could get was via a headless e2e test runner; I couldn't get one in an
actual browser, or other interactive environment. I used the e2e test to
bisect and confirm the fix. But I don't know yet know how to write a
regression test for the precise underlying scenario. I can probably
reverse engineer one by studying the code; after a quick glance
at `performConcurrentWorkOnRoot` and `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, it's not
hard to see how this might happen.

In the meantime, I'll revert the recent change that exposed the bug.

I was surprised that this had never come up before, since the code that
assigns `root.finishedLanes` is in an extremely hot path, and it hasn't
changed in a while. The reason is that, before 530027a,
`root.finishedLanes` was only used by the DevTools profiler, which is
probably why we had never noticed any issues. In addition to fixing the
inconsistency, we might also consider making `finishedLanes` a
profiling-only field.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sebmarkbage/react/commits/bb88ce95a87934a655ef842af776c164391131ac"},{"sha":"9d48779b362ef773da50fef95af6998b560c75c0","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fixed broken feature flag import for DT inline package (#21237)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sebmarkbage/react/commits/9d48779b362ef773da50fef95af6998b560c75c0"},{"sha":"dd8552ae0d82afed66fec649ee5c044c69c65e92","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"yarn test: Default to bleeding edge configuration (#21238)

My personal workflow is to develop against the www-modern release
channel, with the variant flags enabled, because it encompasses the
largest set of features. Then I rely on CI to run the tests against
all the other configurations.

So in practice, I almost always run

```
yarn test -r=www-modern --variant TEST_FILE
```

instead of

```
yarn test TEST_FILE
```

So, I've updated the `yarn test` command to use those options
by default.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sebmarkbage/react/commits/dd8552ae0d82afed66fec649ee5c044c69c65e92"}]

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU

but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

[{"sha":"c8574537bdcae1f9c92d058da4bed63270a9f099","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/c8574537bdcae1f9c92d058da4bed63270a9f099"}]

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

[{"sha":"d292026e26e5098bc751eca2e2e3c29191dadf68","author":{"name":"Jiajun Wang","email":"9aafcb59640c5ea54c57c4c0f0b46ed999af8e22@linkedin.com"},"message":"Directly use Best Possible State to calculate DifferenceWithIdealStateGauge metrics instead of relying on the persisted IdealState.

This PR aims to resolve the undesired dependencies between DifferenceWithIdealStateGauge metric and the PERSIST_XXXXXX_ASSIGNMENT configuration. Before the change, if the assignment is not persisted, then the metric will report incorrect data.
To fix the issue, the calculation must be moved from the ExternalViewComputeStage to the BestPossibleStateCalcStage. Because the Best Possible State is only available in the BestPossibleStateCalcStage assuming the PERSIST_XXXXXX_ASSIGNMENT option is not turned on. In addition to the main logic migration, other changes listed following are required to ensure multi-thread safty.
1. Concurrent control the EV cache since it will now be read in the BestPossibleStateCalcStage in addition to the ExternalViewComputeStage.
2. Minor changes in the diff computing logic for the corner cases since the Best Possible State state mapping is not exactly the same as IdealState persist assignment.
3. Cleanup PersistAssignmentStage logic so it won't modify the IdealState cache anymore. It is supposed to be read-only.
4. Test cases are modified to cover the changes. Also the metric is now reporting correct result in some corner cases such as all the nodes are disabled. The test cases which are testing based on the wrong behavior have been fixed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiajunwang/helix/commits/d292026e26e5098bc751eca2e2e3c29191dadf68"}]

Change-Id: I13e1daf113c490d48bef11d981bd02fd8eb50d02","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/e9e46e402517fdc2a80c9857dc5278493b6250c0"},{"sha":"44b9b8339c5065c2970b828f8a00692ef58e200f","author":{"name":"Mehdi Amini","email":"808100943be7b7010123d78912f654820a5ee1c1@google.com"},"message":"Add support to MLIR TensorFlow dialect for "placeholder attributes"

The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

[{"sha":"27fea8817e625e44761e44c33fd051024b965bec","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a

The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

[{"sha":"5595f9638879c55e4a467d8b0e3d0f6fabb462a8","author":{"name":"Jiajun Wang","email":"9aafcb59640c5ea54c57c4c0f0b46ed999af8e22@linkedin.com"},"message":"Directly use Best Possible State to calculate DifferenceWithIdealStateGauge metrics instead of relying on the persisted IdealState.

This PR aims to resolve the undesired dependencies between DifferenceWithIdealStateGauge metric and the PERSIST_XXXXXX_ASSIGNMENT configuration. Before the change, if the assignment is not persisted, then the metric will report incorrect data.
To fix the issue, the calculation must be moved from the ExternalViewComputeStage to the BestPossibleStateCalcStage. Because the Best Possible State is only available in the BestPossibleStateCalcStage assuming the PERSIST_XXXXXX_ASSIGNMENT option is not turned on. In addition to the main logic migration, other changes listed following are required to ensure multi-thread safty.
1. Concurrent control the EV cache since it will now be read in the BestPossibleStateCalcStage in addition to the ExternalViewComputeStage.
2. Minor changes in the diff computing logic for the corner cases since the Best Possible State state mapping is not exactly the same as IdealState persist assignment.
3. Cleanup PersistAssignmentStage logic so it won't modify the IdealState cache anymore. It is supposed to be read-only.
4. Test cases are modified to cover the changes. Also the metric is now reporting correct result in some corner cases such as all the nodes are disabled. The test cases which are testing based on the wrong behavior have been fixed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiajunwang/helix/commits/5595f9638879c55e4a467d8b0e3d0f6fabb462a8"}]

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sebmarkbage/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sebmarkbage/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.
